            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","procurement","freight","currency","incoterm","receiving"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## PO Shipping, Currency & Freight\n\nBeyond the parts and prices, a purchase order carries the commercial terms that determine landed cost: who pays the freight, in what currency the vendor quoted, and how much shipping actually cost when the goods arrive. This article covers the Shipping & Currency section on a PO and the freight-capture step inside receiving.\n\n### Shipping & Currency on a PO\n\nWhen you create a PO, the sidebar has a **Shipping & Currency** section with three fields. These pre-fill from the preferred vendor-part defaults at create time, and you can override them.\n\n- **Incoterm** — the international commerce term (Incoterms 2020) that defines who arranges and pays for transport, who insures, and when title transfers. Examples: **EXW** (Ex Works — buyer arranges all transport), **FOB Origin** (buyer takes title at the shipping point — the common US-domestic default), **FOB Destination** (seller retains title to your dock), **CFR/CIF/CPT/CIP** (seller pays freight), **DAP/DPU** (delivered at place), and **DDP** (Delivered Duty Paid — seller pays freight and duty). Freight-paid-by-seller terms default the line's freight-included treatment.\n- **Estimated Freight** — your expected shipping cost for the order, entered as a currency amount. It feeds the order summary (Subtotal + Estimated Freight = Total) and the below-vendor-minimum check.\n- **Quote Currency** — the currency the vendor quoted in (USD, EUR, GBP, CAD, MXN, JPY, CNY, and any currency an admin has added to the reference-data currency list). Defaults to USD.\n\n### Editing Shipping & Currency Later\n\nThe PO detail panel shows the same Shipping & Currency block, and while the PO is still in **Draft** an **Edit** button appears next to it. The edit dialog lets you change the Incoterm, Estimated Freight, Quote Currency, and also set the **FX Rate** and **FX Rate Source** (e.g., the rate provider or the date you pulled it). Once the PO leaves Draft, these become read-only.\n\n### FX Rate — Locked at Submit\n\nFor a foreign-currency PO, the exchange rate used to convert the vendor's quote into your home currency is **locked when you submit** the PO. This freezes the home-currency value of the commitment at the moment you place the order, so later currency swings don't silently re-value the PO. The locked **FX Rate** and its **Source** are displayed in the Shipping & Currency block on the detail panel. If you need to correct the rate before submitting, use the Draft edit dialog described above.\n\n### Below-Vendor-Minimum Warning\n\nIf the PO total (lines plus estimated freight) falls under the vendor's minimum order amount, the detail panel shows a non-blocking **below vendor minimum** banner with the minimum amount. It is informational — it does not stop you from submitting — but it's a prompt to consolidate the order or add lines so you clear the vendor's minimum.\n\n### Freight Capture at Receipt\n\nEstimated freight is what you expected; **actual freight** is what the shipment really cost. You record it when the goods arrive. The Receive Items dialog has a **Shipping & Currency** section below the line quantities:\n\n- **Actual Freight** — the real freight charge for this receipt. It **defaults to the PO's estimated freight** so the common 'matches the estimate' case is one click. Override it with the figure from the carrier invoice or packing documents.\n- **Freight Allocation Method** — how the freight cost is spread across the received lines for landed-cost purposes:\n  - **By Extended Value (default)** — allocate proportionally to each line's extended value (quantity times unit price). Higher-value lines absorb more freight.\n  - **By Quantity** — allocate proportionally to the units received on each line. Every unit carries the same freight share regardless of price.\n  - **Manual (per-line)** — you assign the freight split yourself, line by line.\n\n### Freight Variance\n\nWhen the actual freight you enter differs from the PO's estimate, a **Variance** chip appears next to the freight fields showing the percentage difference. It is color-coded as a quick signal — informational, within roughly ±10%; cautionary in the mid range; and prominent when the actual freight is far off the estimate (beyond about ±25%). The variance never blocks the receipt; it simply flags receipts where the freight came in materially different from plan, which is useful for reviewing estimates and vendor performance.\n\n### Putting It Together\n\nA typical flow: pick the Incoterm and enter an estimated freight when you build the PO → the FX rate locks when you submit a foreign-currency order → when the shipment lands, open Receive Items, confirm or override the actual freight, choose an allocation method, and save. The PO now carries both the planned and the actual freight, allocated to the right lines for accurate landed cost.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Auto-PO Suggestions & Settings (Article) ─────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Auto-PO Suggestions & Settings",
            Slug = "purchase-orders-auto-po-settings",
            Summary = "How the nightly demand-analysis job turns unmet demand into purchase-order suggestions, and how an admin enables Auto-PO, picks the Suggest / Draft / Automatic mode, sets buffer days, and toggles chat notifications.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders/settings","/purchase-orders/suggestions"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","procurement","auto-po","automation","admin"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Auto-PO Suggestions & Settings\n\nAuto-PO is the procurement automation that watches demand and proposes the purchase orders you need to cover it — so buyers spend their time reviewing and approving rather than hunting for shortfalls. It lives on the Purchase Orders page across two tabs: **Suggestions** (where the proposals appear) and **Settings** (admin-only, where you configure the behavior).\n\n### How It Works\n\nA **nightly demand-analysis job** scans open demand — primarily sales-order requirements and stock that has fallen below its reorder point — against incoming supply (open POs) and on-hand inventory. Wherever there is unmet, time-phased demand, it groups the shortfall by part and preferred vendor and produces an **Auto-PO suggestion**: which part, which vendor, the suggested quantity, the date it's needed by, and the source sales orders that drove the demand.\n\nThe job runs automatically every night. An admin can also force a run on demand from the Suggestions tab (see the Auto-PO Suggestions walkthrough) rather than waiting for the overnight cycle.\n\n### Three Modes\n\nThe **Default Mode** setting controls what the nightly job does with the suggestions it produces:\n\n- **Suggest** — the job only creates suggestions. Nothing is ordered automatically. A buyer reviews each suggestion on the Suggestions tab and decides whether to convert it to a PO or dismiss it. This is the most conservative mode and the usual starting point.\n- **Draft** — the job goes one step further and creates **Draft** purchase orders from the suggestions, but stops there. The Drafts wait on the Orders tab for a buyer to review, adjust, and submit. You get the time savings of pre-built POs while keeping a human gate before anything is sent to a vendor.\n- **Automatic** — the job creates the purchase orders without a manual gate. Use this only for trusted, well-tuned replenishment where the demand signal and vendor terms are reliable.\n\n### Settings Fields (Admin)\n\nThe **Settings** tab is visible only to admins. It has:\n\n- **Enable Auto-PO** — the master switch. When off, the nightly job does not generate suggestions or POs. Turn this on before any of the other settings take effect.\n- **Default Mode** — Suggest, Draft, or Automatic, as described above. Required.\n- **Buffer Days** — a lead-time cushion (0–365). The job pulls demand forward by this many days so a suggestion is raised early enough to order, ship, and receive before the need date. Larger buffers order earlier and carry more stock; smaller buffers order later and run leaner. Required.\n- **Notify Chat** — when enabled, the system posts a message to chat after a run so the team sees that new suggestions (or POs) are waiting, without having to watch the tab.\n\nMake your changes and click **Save**. The Save button is disabled until the form is valid and you've changed something.\n\n### Capability & Roles\n\nAuto-PO is gated by the **CAP-P2P-AUTOPO** capability — if it's disabled for your install, the Suggestions and Settings tabs won't function. Viewing and acting on suggestions is available to **Admin, Manager, and Office Manager** roles; **editing the Settings and triggering an on-demand run are Admin-only**.\n\n### Choosing a Mode\n\nMost shops start in **Suggest**, build trust in the demand signal, then graduate the reliable categories to **Draft** so POs are pre-staged for a quick review. Reserve **Automatic** for the parts where you'd rubber-stamp every suggestion anyway. You can change the mode at any time — it only affects future nightly runs.","sections":[]}"""
        });

