            AppRoutes = """["/purchase-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["purchase-orders","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Off-Tier Price Prompt\n\nWhen you save a PO, the dialog calls `POST /api/v1/vendor-parts/check-tier-variance` with every line. The server matches each line against the vendor-part price tier for the same purchase option (so the comparison is apples-to-apples) and flags any line whose entered price differs from the tier price by more than the configured `thresholdPct`.\n\nIf one or more lines come back `isOffTier`, a single consolidated **off-tier prompt** fires for the whole PO (not one prompt per line). Each listed row shows the part, the current tier price (or 'no tier' when none exists), the entered price, and the variance pct. Per row, the buyer chooses:\n\n- **Record as exception (default)** — the line is saved at the entered price as a one-off. Master pricing is untouched. This is the default precisely so tier changes are opt-in and master pricing isn't accidentally polluted.\n- **Update tier** — inserts a new `VendorPartPriceTier` at the entered price and the line quantity, effective today. Subsequent POs then see the new baseline.\n\nFooter actions: **Cancel** returns to the PO dialog; **Continue** commits the per-row choices, then proceeds with PO submission.\n\n## Per-Line Price Override & Reason Audit\n\nWhen a part is selected, the line's unit price auto-fills from the resolved tier/effective price and is marked as the default. Manually changing a default-filled price is gated (logic in `classifyManualOverride`):\n\n- **Permission** — only **Admin** and **Manager** may override a default-filled price. Other users are reverted to the computed price with an 'override requires permission' message.\n- **Reason** — an authorized override prompts for a justification. A blank reason reverts the price; a non-blank reason is recorded as `manualOverrideReason` and attached to the line when it's added.\n\nThe reason persists to `PurchaseOrderLine.ManualOverrideReason` and is returned by `GetPurchaseOrderById`, so the override is auditable on the PO. (A change to a non-default price, or any edit by an entered-from-scratch line, does not trigger the reason prompt.)\n\n## AI Price-Variance Review\n\nA buyer can ask for an AI-assisted assessment of a price override via `POST /api/v1/purchase-orders/price-variance-review` (gated by **CAP-EXT-AI-ASSISTANT**). The handler has two halves:\n\n- **Deterministic** — reuses the same option-aware tier match as the off-tier prompt to compute `tierPrice` and `variancePct`, then bands a `riskLevel`: **Low** when on-tier, **High** when variance > 25%, otherwise **Medium**. It also builds a templated `suggestedJustification` (entered vs tier price, variance, qty, and the buyer's reason).\n- **AI (best-effort)** — when the model is online, returns a 2–3 sentence narrative `assessment` flagging red flags. When the model is offline, `aiAvailable` is false and a templated assessment is returned instead, so the review degrades gracefully and never blocks.\n\n## PO Barcode / QR Label\n\nThe PO detail panel renders an `app-barcode-info` block keyed off the PO with the PO number as the natural identifier (`entityType=\"PurchaseOrder\"`). It fetches the entity's barcodes (`getEntityBarcodes`), shows the active one as a QR code, and exposes a print-label affordance via `LabelPrintService` (bwip-js generation). This lets the printed PO carry a scannable code that resolves back to the order at receiving.\n\n## PO Calendar Feed\n\nExpected-delivery dates surface on the calendar via `GET /api/v1/purchase-orders/calendar?from=&to=`, which returns `PoCalendarResponseModel` rows (Id, PoNumber, VendorName, ExpectedDeliveryDate, Status, LineCount) for the requested window. Separately, the install's outbound **ICS feed** (`IcsCalendarFeedService`, provider id `ics_feed`) is read-only — it generates `BEGIN:VCALENDAR` events from app data for subscription in an external calendar; it does not accept pushed events or free/busy queries.\n\n## Draft Auto-Save\n\nThe PO create/edit dialog participates in the shared draft system as a `DraftableForm` with `entityType: 'purchase-order'`. Dirty form state auto-saves to IndexedDB (debounced) and is recovered on next login or revisit; the draft is cleared on a successful save, explicit discard, or TTL expiry. This is a safety net against losing in-progress line entry — it is not a substitute for saving the PO.","sections":[]}"""
        });

